sources.csv: Frequency List; Newspaper Corpus; dwds-goethe-A1.csv; learn-deutsch-data:nouns
sources.notes: regional usage; https://www.dwds.de/wb/Haus; Nouns ending in -us, -ma, -um, -ment, -lein, -chen are often neuter (das). Many one-syllable nouns take an umlaut and "-er" in the plural.

examples.de: 1545, Martin Luther, Biblia: das ist: Die gantze Heilige Schrifft: Deudsch Auffs new zugericht, Moses I (Genesis) 1:1
examples.en: In the beginning, God created heaven and earth.

sources.notes: https://www.dwds.de/wb/Apfel; Masculine nouns often have plurals with an umlaut and no ending, or just an umlaut.
https://www.dwds.de/wb/Flughafen; Compound nouns take the gender of the last word (der Hafen). The plural often follows the last word's plural form.
https://www.dwds.de/wb/Frau; Feminine nouns often form the plural by adding "-en" or "-n".
Nouns ending in -ung, -heit, -keit, -schaft, -ei are always feminine (die) and add "-en" in the plural.
